    <item>
      <title>Last Preview of 2024 (Probably)</title>
      <author>Daniel Schuman       </author>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/461/2024-12-16_last-preview-of-2024-probably</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/461/2024-12-16_last-preview-of-2024-probably</guid>
      <pubDate>Mon, 16 Dec 2024 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>                &lt;p&gt;Good morning, Govtrekkers!&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;This is the last week we anticipate Congress will be in session until the 119th Congress starts on January 3rd. However, as of the time of this writing, the text for the Continuing Resolution to fund the government has not been published, the Senate has not considered the National Defense Authorization Act, and Senator Schumer is trying to push through a number of judicial confirmations. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Looking at the&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;a href="https://www.majorityleader.gov/schedule/weekly-schedule.htm"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;House floor&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt;, there are three bills expected to be considered that can pass with a simple majority and dozens of bills that may reach a 2/3rds majority to pass under fast-track rules. The three bills needing a simple majority are the Continuing Resolution (CR), the “Supplemental Pay-for,” and the Midnight Rules Relief Act. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;There is no text available yet for either the CR or the supplemental pay-for. The CR is anticipated to provide funds to keep the government open (otherwise a shutdown would occur on Friday) and will carry a number of additional measures, the contours of which are currently being negotiated. As of Monday morning, we still have not seen the text of the CR because of a fight over legislative riders, particularly &lt;a href="https://www.politico.com/news/2024/12/15/johnson-farm-aid-deadline-00194390"&gt;farm aid&lt;/a&gt;. I haven’t been following the “supplemental pay-for” and do not know what it would do. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Midnight Rules Relief Act is a resolution that would allow Congress to more easily invalidate regulations issued within the final days of a president’s term instead of having to enact one resolution per regulation. In other words, instead of voting on each resolution that would undo a single agency regulation, lawmakers would vote on a package that would invalidate multiple regulations at once. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Republican leadership floor notice says there are thirty-three bills “on suspension,” which is a fast track procedure for uncontroversial bills, but the &lt;a href="https://docs.house.gov/floor/Default.aspx?date=2024-12-16"&gt;webpage&lt;/a&gt; where the resolutions must be posted contains fifty-one, and that number may grow. There is no rhyme or reason to the left-overs, although I do see a number related to congressional operations. Is it worth Congress’s time to designate the bald eagle as the national bird? To rename the Veterans Affairs clinic in Oklahoma after Sen. Inhofe? Other substantive bills, such as those concerning organ donation and reducing child abuse, are coming up very late in the game — but late is better than never for those that support them.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;There are eight congressional meetings this week&lt;/strong&gt;, including the House Rules Committee on Monday which will tee-up the three simple majority bills, setting the terms for debate and whether amendments can be offered. This is where leadership will make changes to the text of the bills to comply with whatever deal they’ve made with members and with the Senate on what will become law. I am surprised to see the House Veterans Affairs Committee holding a hearing on a range of bills because of the late date. The Senate Finance committee will hold hearings on nominees to the US International Trade Commission. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Senate Democrats&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;a href="https://www.democrats.senate.gov/floor/senate-schedule"&gt;announced&lt;/a&gt; Monday’s Senate floor schedule, which will include efforts to end debate and vote on the National Defense Authorization Act and the Social Security Fairness Act. Presumably, later this week will include consideration of the Continuing Resolution. Schumer will spend much of the remaining floor time focused on confirming federal judges. A big question remains as to whether he will keep his process to try to enact the journalist shield law known as the PRESS Act.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;My colleague Amy will provide an update on the status of all this legislation at the end of the week. It’s doubtful that I’ll be back next week to give a preview of congressional activity as Congress likely will not be in session, but I do want to alert you to a few things. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Over the next few weeks, both parties will finalize their selections for committee leadership. In the House, Republicans will finalize their recommendations for the rules of the House of Representatives, which likely will become publicly available only the day before it’s adopted on January 3rd. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;In the Senate, Republicans and Democrats will be negotiating over the organizing resolution for the chamber, which appoints people to various committees and decides other policies. In addition, we can expect Republicans to move quickly towards confirmation of key Trump appointees and likely will schedule confirmation hearings in the run up to the inauguration on January 20th.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I expect the 119th Congress will be even more unconventional than the 118th. Much of what we have come to expect regarding the roles of the executive and legislative branches will be subject to change and Congress will try to move quickly to enact Trump’s agenda. The major limitation will be discerning what exactly he wants to do.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Have a good holiday season.&lt;/p&gt;      </description>
      <category>&amp;middot; Legislative Preview 	&amp;middot; by Daniel Schuman 	</category>
